{"title_page": "We the People.... (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = We the People....\n| cover      = Wethepeopletribe.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[A Tribe Called Quest]]\n| album      = [[We Got It from Here\u2026 Thank You 4 Your Service]]\n| released   = November 17, 2016<ref name=\"avclub\"/>\n| format     = [[music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Alternative hip hop]]\n*[[political hip hop]]<ref name=\"billboard\"/>}}\n| length     = 2:52\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Q-Tip (musician)|Kamaal Fareed]]\n*[[Phife Dawg|Malik Taylor]]\n*[[Geezer Butler|Terrance Butler]]\n*[[Tony Iommi|Anthony Iommi]]\n*[[Ozzy Osbourne|John Osbourne]]\n*[[Bill Ward (musician)|William Ward]]}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]]\n*Blair Wells {{small|(co.)}}}}\n| prev_title = [[Like It Like That (A Tribe Called Quest song)|Like It Like That]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = Dis Generation\n| next_year  = 2017\n|misc={{External music video|{{YouTube|vO2Su3erRIA|\"We The People....\"}}}}}}\n\"'''We the People....'''\" is a song by American [[hip hop music|hip hop]] group [[A Tribe Called Quest]], and the first single from their sixth and final album, ''[[We Got It from Here\u2026 Thank You 4 Your Service]]''.<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web | url=http://www.avclub.com/article/tribe-called-quest-sounds-alarm-first-video-its-ne-246156 | title=A Tribe Called Quest sounds the alarm in the first video from its new album | work=The A.V. Club | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Produced by [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] and co-produced by Blair Wells, the song contains a sample of the [[break (music)|drum break]] of \"Behind the Wall of Sleep\" by [[Black Sabbath]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/69742-here-are-the-full-credits-for-the-new-tribe-called-quest-album/|title=Here Are the Full Credits for the New Tribe Called Quest Album|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|date=November 12, 2016|access-date=January 10, 2017}}</ref> The chorus of the politically-charged song parodies [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"billboard\"/> \"We the People....\" was critically acclaimed and included on several year-end lists by critics.<ref name=\"billboard\"/><ref name=\"pazzjop\"/><ref name=\"pitchfork\"/><ref name=\"consequence\"/><ref name=\"npr\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nOn November 13, 2015, A Tribe Called Quest reunited and performed on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', on the same night of the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris attacks]]. Inspired by the energy of their performance, the group members put aside their differences and began recording a new album, ''We Got It from Here... Thank You 4 Your Service'', shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"toure\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/arts/music/a-tribe-called-quest-new-album-interview.html?_r=0 | title=Loss Haunts A Tribe Called Quest\u2019s First Album in 18 Years | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 2, 2016 | accessdate=January 10, 2017 | author=Tour\u00e9}}</ref> \"We the People....\" was one of the first songs recorded for the album, as it featured a verse from group member [[Phife Dawg]], who died on March 22, 2016 before the album's completion.<ref name=\"toure\"/>\n \n== Critical reception ==\nJayson Greene of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called the song \"a ferocious and driving song about intolerance and fear,\" adding that it \"simply put, is a sliver-sized miracle, a crack of light illuminating the door in a dark wall. This is the function Tribe songs have always served\u2014they point to a path through wilderness.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18610-a-tribe-called-quest-we-the-people/ | title=A Tribe Called Quest - \"We the People...\" | author=Greene, Jayson | work=Pitchfork | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Gil Kaufman of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' praised the song, noting that it \"instantly became the national anthem of the anti-Trump nation.\"<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2016/7617635/billboard-top-100-pop-songs-of-2016 | title=Billboard's 100 Best Pop Songs of 2016: Critics' Picks | author=Kaufman, Gil | work=Billboard | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2016, ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' named it the best single of the year, while ''[[The Village Voice]]'' ranked it fifth in their annual [[Pazz & Jop]] critics poll.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 25 Best Singles of 2016 |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/the-25-best-singles-of-2016/P5 |website=Slant Magazine |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pazzjop\">{{cite web | url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/singles/2016 | title=Pazz+Jop 2016 | work=The Village Voice | accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> ''Billboard'' ranked it the 10th best song of the year, while ''Pitchfork'' ranked it 11th, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' ranked it 25th, and [[NPR]] ranked it 34th.<ref name=\"billboard\"/><ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9981-the-100-best-songs-of-2016/?page=9 | title=The 100 Best Songs of 2016 | author=Walls, Seth Colter | work=Pitchfork | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"consequence\">{{cite web | url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/12/top-50-songs-of-2016/4/ | title=Top 50 Songs of 2016 | author=Sterling, Scott T. | work=Consequence of Sound | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web | url=http://apps.npr.org/best-music-2016/list/top-songs/ | title=Top 100 Songs Of 2016 | work=NPR | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nThe music video was directed by James Larese. It begins with several people running through the streets of [[New York City]], as Q-Tip performs his verse, standing in front of more than a dozen microphones. He is joined by [[Jarobi White]], [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] (who appears on a TV screen), [[Busta Rhymes]], and [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]]. Before Phife Dawg's verse begins, a mural of his face is shown on the side of a building; the mural becomes animated throughout his verse. The video ends with hundreds of people gathered in a city square, surrounded by many signs reading \"We the People.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.spin.com/2016/11/video-a-tribe-called-quest-we-the-people/ | title=Video: A Tribe Called Quest \u2013 \"We the People\" | author=McGovern, Kyle | work=Spin | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2016)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|77|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|77|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|31|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrapsongs|23|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Preamble to the United States Constitution]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{A Tribe Called Quest}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:We the People}}\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:A Tribe Called Quest songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Political rap songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Q-Tip (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs against racism and xenophobia]]\n[[Category:Songs released posthumously]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bill Ward (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Geezer Butler]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ozzy Osbourne]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Phife Dawg]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Q-Tip (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tony Iommi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = We the People....\n| cover      = Wethepeopletribe.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[A Tribe Called Quest]]\n| album      = [[We Got It from Here... Thank You 4 Your Service]]\n| released   = November 17, 2016<ref name=\"avclub\"/>\n| format     = [[music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Alternative hip hop]]\n*[[political hip hop]]<ref name=\"billboard\"/>}}\n| length     = 2:52\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Q-Tip (musician)|Kamaal Fareed]]\n*[[Phife Dawg|Malik Taylor]]\n*[[Geezer Butler|Terrance Butler]]\n*[[Tony Iommi|Anthony Iommi]]\n*[[Ozzy Osbourne|John Osbourne]]\n*[[Bill Ward (musician)|William Ward]]}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]]\n*Blair Wells {{small|(co.)}}}}\n| prev_title = [[Like It Like That (A Tribe Called Quest song)|Like It Like That]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[We Got It from Here... Thank You 4 Your Service|Dis Generation]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n|misc={{External music video|{{YouTube|vO2Su3erRIA|\"We The People....\"}}}}}}\n\"'''We the People....'''\" is a song by American [[hip hop music|hip hop]] group [[A Tribe Called Quest]], and the first single from their sixth and final album, ''[[We Got It from Here... Thank You 4 Your Service]]''.<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web | url=http://www.avclub.com/article/tribe-called-quest-sounds-alarm-first-video-its-ne-246156 | title=A Tribe Called Quest sounds the alarm in the first video from its new album | work=The A.V. Club | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Produced by [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] and co-produced by Blair Wells, the song contains a sample of the [[break (music)|drum break]] of \"Behind the Wall of Sleep\" by [[Black Sabbath]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/69742-here-are-the-full-credits-for-the-new-tribe-called-quest-album/|title=Here Are the Full Credits for the New Tribe Called Quest Album|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|date=November 12, 2016|access-date=January 10, 2017}}</ref> The chorus of the politically-charged song parodies [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"billboard\"/> \"We the People....\" was critically acclaimed and included on several year-end lists by critics.<ref name=\"billboard\"/><ref name=\"pazzjop\"/><ref name=\"pitchfork\"/><ref name=\"consequence\"/><ref name=\"npr\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nOn November 13, 2015, A Tribe Called Quest reunited and performed on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', on the same night of the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris attacks]]. Inspired by the energy of their performance, the group members put aside their differences and began recording a new album, ''We Got It from Here... Thank You 4 Your Service'', shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"toure\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/arts/music/a-tribe-called-quest-new-album-interview.html?_r=0 | title=Loss Haunts A Tribe Called Quest\u2019s First Album in 18 Years | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 2, 2016 | accessdate=January 10, 2017 | author=Tour\u00e9}}</ref> \"We the People....\" was one of the first songs recorded for the album, as it featured a verse from group member [[Phife Dawg]], who died on March 22, 2016 before the album's completion.<ref name=\"toure\"/>\n \n== Critical reception ==\nJayson Greene of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called the song \"a ferocious and driving song about intolerance and fear,\" adding that it \"simply put, is a sliver-sized miracle, a crack of light illuminating the door in a dark wall. This is the function Tribe songs have always served\u2014they point to a path through wilderness.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18610-a-tribe-called-quest-we-the-people/ | title=A Tribe Called Quest - \"We the People...\" | author=Greene, Jayson | work=Pitchfork | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Gil Kaufman of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' praised the song, noting that it \"instantly became the national anthem of the anti-Trump nation.\"<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2016/7617635/billboard-top-100-pop-songs-of-2016 | title=Billboard's 100 Best Pop Songs of 2016: Critics' Picks | author=Kaufman, Gil | work=Billboard | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2016, ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' named it the best single of the year, while ''[[The Village Voice]]'' ranked it fifth in their annual [[Pazz & Jop]] critics poll.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 25 Best Singles of 2016 |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/the-25-best-singles-of-2016/P5 |website=Slant Magazine |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pazzjop\">{{cite web | url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/singles/2016 | title=Pazz+Jop 2016 | work=The Village Voice | accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> ''Billboard'' ranked it the 10th best song of the year, while ''Pitchfork'' ranked it 11th, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' ranked it 25th, and [[NPR]] ranked it 34th.<ref name=\"billboard\"/><ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9981-the-100-best-songs-of-2016/?page=9 | title=The 100 Best Songs of 2016 | author=Walls, Seth Colter | work=Pitchfork | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"consequence\">{{cite web | url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/12/top-50-songs-of-2016/4/ | title=Top 50 Songs of 2016 | author=Sterling, Scott T. | work=Consequence of Sound | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web | url=http://apps.npr.org/best-music-2016/list/top-songs/ | title=Top 100 Songs Of 2016 | work=NPR | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nThe music video was directed by James Larese. It begins with several people running through the streets of [[New York City]], as Q-Tip performs his verse, standing in front of more than a dozen microphones. He is joined by [[Jarobi White]], [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] (who appears on a TV screen), [[Busta Rhymes]], and [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]]. Before Phife Dawg's verse begins, a mural of his face is shown on the side of a building; the mural becomes animated throughout his verse. The video ends with hundreds of people gathered in a city square, surrounded by many signs reading \"We the People.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.spin.com/2016/11/video-a-tribe-called-quest-we-the-people/ | title=Video: A Tribe Called Quest \u2013 \"We the People\" | author=McGovern, Kyle | work=Spin | accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2016)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|77|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|77|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|31|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrapsongs|23|artist=A Tribe Called Quest|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Preamble to the United States Constitution]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{A Tribe Called Quest}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:We the People}}\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:A Tribe Called Quest songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Political rap songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Q-Tip (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs against racism and xenophobia]]\n[[Category:Songs released posthumously]]\n[[Category