{"title_page": "Ogura Hyakunin Isshu", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n[[Image:Hyakuninisshu 001.jpg|thumb|First poem card of the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', featuring [[Emperor Tenji]]]]\n[[Image:Ogura Shikishi.jpg|thumb|Ogura ''{{wt|ja|\u8272\u7d19|shikishi}}'' by Teika]]\n{{nihongo|'''''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'''''|\u5c0f\u5009\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}} is a classical Japanese anthology of one hundred Japanese [[Waka (poetry)|''waka'']] by one hundred poets. ''Hyakunin isshu'' can be translated to \"one hundred people, one poem [each]\"; it can also refer to the card game of ''[[uta-garuta]]'', which uses a deck composed of cards based on the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''.\n\nIt was compiled by [[Fujiwara no Teika]] while he lived in the [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Ogura district]] of [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]].<ref>Mostow, Joshua. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA25&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image,'' p.25.]</ref>\n\n==Compilation==\nOne of Teika's diaries, the ''Meigetsuki'', says that his son [[Fujiwara no Tameie|Tameie]] asked him to arrange one hundred poems for Tameie's father-in-law, [[Utsunomiya Yoritsuna]], who was furnishing a residence near [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Mount Ogura]];<ref>Ogurayama: Latitude: 34\u00b0 53' 60 N, Longitude: 135\u00b0 46' 60 E; Kyoto Prefecture web site: [http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search  northwest of Arashiyama Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112301/http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search |date=2011-07-22 }}.</ref> hence the full name of ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''. In order to decorate screens of the residence, [[Fujiwara no Teika]] produced the calligraphy poem sheets.<ref>Mostow, [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA94&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  p.94.]</ref>\n\n[[Hishikawa Moronobu]] provided woodblock portraits for each of the poets included in the anthology.<ref name=\"wdl2929\">{{cite web|title=100 Poems by 100 Poets|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/2929/|website=[[World Digital Library]]|date=1680|accessdate=7 June 2013|language=Japanese|author1=Hishikawa, Moronobu\n|author2=Fujiwara, Sadaie}}</ref>\n\nIn his own lifetime, Teika was better known for other work.  For example, in 1200 (''Sh\u014dji 2''), Teika prepared another anthology of one hundred poems for ex-[[Emperor Go-Toba]]. This was called the ''Sh\u014dji Hyakushu''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brower|first=Robert H.|title=Fujiwara Teika's Hundred-Poem Sequence of the Sh\u014dji Era|jstor=2384210|journal=[[Monumenta Nipponica]]|volume=31|issue=3|date=Autumn 1976|pages=223\u2013249|doi=10.2307/2384210}}</ref>\n\n==Poets==\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor Tenji]]|\u5929\u667a\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Empress Jit\u014d]]|\u6301\u7d71\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kakinomoto no Hitomaro]]|\u67ff\u672c\u4eba\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Yamabe no Akahito]]|\u5c71\u90e8\u8d64\u4eba}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sarumaru Day\u016b]]|\u733f\u4e38\u5927\u592b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ch\u016bnagon|Middle Councillor]] [[\u014ctomo no Yakamochi|Yakamochi]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5bb6\u6301}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Abe no Nakamaro]]|\u963f\u500d\u4ef2\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Kisen]]|\u559c\u64b0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ono no Komachi]]|\u5c0f\u91ce\u5c0f\u753a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Semimaru]]|\u8749\u4e38}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Ono no Takamura|Takamura]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7bc1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[High priest|High Priest]] [[Henj\u014d]]|\u50e7\u6b63\u904d\u662d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Y\u014dzei]]|\u967d\u6210\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no T\u014dru|Minister of the Left of Kawara]]|\u6cb3\u539f\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor K\u014dk\u014d]]|\u5149\u5b5d\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Ariwara no Yukihira|Yukihira]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u884c\u5e73}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ariwara no Narihira]] ''[[Ason]]''|\u5728\u539f\u696d\u5e73\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Toshiyuki]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u654f\u884c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Lady Ise|Ise]]|\u4f0a\u52e2}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Prince Motoyoshi]]|\u5143\u826f\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Sosei]]|\u7d20\u6027\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Yasuhide]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u5eb7\u79c0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014ce no Chisato]]|\u5927\u6c5f\u5343\u91cc}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sugawara no Michizane|Kanke]]|\u83c5\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sadakata|Minister of the Right of Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadahira|Teishin-k\u014d]]|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Kanesuke|Kanesuke]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u517c\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Muneyuki]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u5b97\u4e8e\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cshik\u014dchi no Mitsune]]|\u51e1\u6cb3\u5185\u8eac\u6052}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadamine]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u5c91}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sakanoue no Korenori]]|\u5742\u4e0a\u662f\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Harumichi no Tsuraki]]|\u6625\u9053\u5217\u6a39}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tomonori]]|\u7d00\u53cb\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Okikaze]]|\u85e4\u539f\u8208\u98a8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tsurayuki]]|\u7d00\u8cab\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Fukayabu]]|\u6e05\u539f\u6df1\u990a\u7236}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Asayasu]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u671d\u5eb7}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ukon (poet)|Ukon]]|\u53f3\u8fd1}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Minamoto no Hitoshi|Hitoshi]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7b49}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taira no Kanemori]]|\u5e73\u517c\u76db}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadami]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u898b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Motosuke]]|\u6e05\u539f\u5143\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Atsutada|Atsutada]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u6566\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Asatada|Asatada]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u671d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Koretada|Kentoku-k\u014d]]|\u8b19\u5fb3\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sone no Yoshitada]]|\u66fd\u79b0\u597d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Egy\u014d]]|\u6075\u6176\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Shigeyuki]]|\u6e90\u91cd\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cnakatomi no Yoshinobu]] ''Ason''|\u5927\u4e2d\u81e3\u80fd\u5ba3\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Yoshitaka]]|\u85e4\u539f\u7fa9\u5b5d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sanekata]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u5b9f\u65b9\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Michinobu]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u9053\u4fe1\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Michitsuna no Haha|Mother of the Right Captain Michitsuna]]|\u53f3\u5927\u5c06\u9053\u7db1\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Takashina no Takako|Mother of the Honorary Grand Minister]]|\u5100\u540c\u4e09\u53f8\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Dainagon|Upper Councillor]] [[Fujiwara no Kint\u014d|Kint\u014d]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u516c\u4efb}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Izumi Shikibu]]|\u548c\u6cc9\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Murasaki Shikibu]]|\u7d2b\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Daini no Sanmi]]|\u5927\u5f10\u4e09\u4f4d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Akazome Emon]]|\u8d64\u67d3\u885b\u9580}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Koshikibu no Naishi]]|\u5c0f\u5f0f\u90e8\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ise no Taifu]]|\u4f0a\u52e2\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sei Sh\u014dnagon]]|\u6e05\u5c11\u7d0d\u8a00}}\n# {{nihongo|Chief Magistrate of the Left [[Fujiwara no Michimasa|Michimasa]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9053\u96c5}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Sadayori|Sadayori]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u983c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sagami (poet)|Sagami]]|\u76f8\u6a21}}\n# {{nihongo|Archbishop [[Gy\u014dson]]|\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u884c\u5c0a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Su\u014d no Naishi]]|\u5468\u9632\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[N\u014din]]|\u80fd\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Ry\u014dzen]]|\u826f\u66b9\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Upper Councillor [[Minamoto no Tsunenobu|Tsunenobu]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u7d4c\u4fe1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Y\u016bshi Naishinn\u014d-ke no Kii|Kii of Princess Y\u016bshi's Household]]|\u7950\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b\u5bb6\u7d00\u4f0a}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[\u014ce no Masafusa|Masafusa]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5321\u623f}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Toshiyori]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u4fca\u983c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Mototoshi]]|\u85e4\u539f\u57fa\u4fca}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadamichi|Lay Priest of Hossh\u014d-ji Temple, former ''Kampaku'' and Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u6cd5\u6027\u5bfa\u5165\u9053\u524d\u95a2\u767d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sutoku]]|\u5d07\u5fb3\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Kanemasa]]|\u6e90\u517c\u660c}}\n# {{nihongo|Chief Magistrate of the Left [[Fujiwara no Akisuke|Akisuke]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9855\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taikenmon'in no Horikawa|Horikawa, attendant to Empress Taiken]]|\u5f85\u8ce2\u9580\u9662\u5800\u6cb3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Tokudaiji Sanesada|Later Tokudaiji Minister of the Left]]|\u5f8c\u5fb3\u5927\u5bfa\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[D\u014din]]|\u9053\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Master of the Empress Dowager's Household [[Fujiwara no Shunzei|Shunzei/Toshinari]]|\u7687\u592a\u540e\u5bae\u5927\u592b\u4fca\u6210}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Kiyosuke]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u6e05\u8f14\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Shun'e]]|\u4fca\u6075\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Saigy\u014d]]|\u897f\u884c\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Jakuren]]|\u5bc2\u84ee\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[K\u014dkamonin no Bett\u014d|Attendant to Empress K\u014dka]]|\u7687\u5609\u9580\u9662\u5225\u5f53}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Princess Shikishi]]|\u5f0f\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Inpumon'in no Tay\u016b|Attendant to Empress Inpu]]|\u6bb7\u5bcc\u9580\u9662\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kuj\u014d Yoshitsune|Goky\u014dgoku Regent and Former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5f8c\u4eac\u6975\u6442\u653f\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Nij\u014din no Sanuki|Sanuki, attendant to retired Emperor Nij\u014d]]|\u4e8c\u6761\u9662\u8b83\u5c90}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Sanetomo|Minister of the Right of Kamakura]]|\u938c\u5009\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Asukai no Masatsune|Masatsune]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u96c5\u7d4c}}\n# {{nihongo|Former Archbishop [[Jien]]|\u524d\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u6148\u5186}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Saionji Kintsune|Lay Priest and Former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5165\u9053\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Teika|Teika/Sadaie]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|Junior Second Rank [[Fujiwara no Ietaka|Ietaka]]|\u5f93\u4e8c\u4f4d\u5bb6\u9686}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Go-Toba]]|\u5f8c\u9ce5\u7fbd\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Juntoku]]|\u9806\u5fb3\u9662}}\n\n==Poems==\n[[File:Hyakunin Isshu.JPG|thumb|right|250px|An [[Edo period|Edo-period]] illustrated ''Hyakunin Isshu'' book, with Priest Kisen and Ono no Komachi.]]\n\n===Poem number 2===\nA visually-descriptive poem attributed to [[Empress Jit\u014d]]. Teika chose this poem from the ''[[Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b]]'':\n\n{{waka\n|\u6625\u904e\u304e\u3066\u590f\u6765\u306b\u3051\u3089\u3057{{wt|ja|\u767d\u5999\u306e}}|\u8863\u5e72\u3059\u3066\u3075\u5929\u306e\u9999\u5177\u5c71\n|reading = haru sugite natsu kinikerashi shirotae no<br/>koromo hosu ch\u014d Ama no Kaguyama\n|translation = Spring has passed, and the white robes of summer are being aired on fragrant Mount Kagu\u2014beloved of the gods.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Teika|translator-last1=MacMillan|translator-first1=Peter|date=2018|title=One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse|publisher=Penguin UK|isbn=9780141395944}}</ref>\n|source = ''Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b'' 3:175\n}}\n\nThe original was likely based from a poem of the ''[[Man'y\u014dsh\u016b]]'' (book 1, poem 28) by the same poet.\n\n===Poem number 26===\nA quite different poem is attributed to ''[[Minister of the Left|Sadaijin]]'' [[Fujiwara no Tadahira]] in the context of a very specific incident.  After abdicating, former [[Emperor Uda]] visited Mount Ogura in [[Yamashiro Province]]. He was so greatly impressed by the beauty of autumn colours of the maples that he ordered Fujiwara no Tadahira to encourage Uda's son and heir, [[Emperor Daigo]], to visit the same area.\n\n{{nihongo|Prince Tenshin or Teishin|{{wt|ja|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}|''Teishin-k\u014d''}} was Tadahira's posthumous name, and this is the name used in William Porter's translation of the poem which observes that \"[t]he maples of Mount Ogura / If they could understand / Would keep their brilliant leaves / until [t]he Ruler of this land / Pass with his Royal band.\"  The accompanying 18th century illustration shows a person of consequence riding an ox in a procession with attendants on foot.  The group is passing through an area of maple leaves.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Sadaie|translator-last1=Porter|translator-first1=William N.|date=2007|title=A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the ''Hyakunin Isshu''|edition=illustrated, reprint|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&pg=PA26&dq=hyakunin+ogura#PPA26,M1|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=9784805308530|pages=25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nTeika chose this poem from the ''[[Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b]]'' for the hundred poems collection:\n\n{{waka|\u5c0f\u5009\u5c71\u5cf0\u306e\u3082\u307f\u3062\u8449\u5fc3\u3042\u3089\u3070|\u4eca\u3072\u3068\u305f\u3073\u306e\u884c\u5e78\u307e\u305f\u306a\u3080|reading = Ogura-yama mine no momijiba kokoro araba<br/>ima hitotabi no miyuki matanan<ref>The modern romanization of the last line would be ''miyuki '''matanamu''''' (\u201cawait the emperor's pilgrimage\u201d); by applying the [[historical kana orthography]], ''matanamu'' would be pronounced ''matana'''n'''''.</ref>|translation = Maple leaves on Ogura mountain: if you had a heart, I would have you wait for one more royal visit!<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kamens|first1=Edward|last2=Kamens|first2=Howard I.|date=1997|title=Utamakura, Allusion, and Intertextuality in Traditional Japanese Poetry|edition=illustrated|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300068085|page=102}}</ref>|source = ''Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b'' 17:1128}}\n\n==English translations==\nThe ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'' has been translated into many languages and into English many times, beginning with [[Yone Noguchi]]'s ''Hyaku Nin Isshu in English'' in 1907.<ref>Yone Noguchi, [http://www.h.ehime-u.ac.jp/-marx/YN/articles/hyakunin.htm Hyaku Nin Isshu in English, ''Waseda Bungaku'' (1907)]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOther translations include:\n* William N. Porter, ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan'' (1909)\n* Clay MacCauley, ''Hyakunin-isshu (Single Songs of a Hundred Poets)'' (1917)\n* Tom Galt, ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each'' (1982)\n* Joshua S. Mostow, ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image'' (1996)\n* Peter MacMillan, ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'' (2008; [[Penguin Classics]], revised edition 2018)\n* Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'' (2008)\n\n==Other Hyakunin Isshu anthologies==\nMany other anthologies compiled along the same criteria\u2014one hundred poems by one hundred poets\u2014include the words ''hyakunin isshu'', notably the [[World War II]]-era {{nihongo|''Aikoku Hyakunin Isshu''|\u611b\u56fd\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, or ''One Hundred Patriotic Poems by One Hundred Poets''. Also important is {{nihongo|''Ky\u014dka Hyakunin Isshu''|\u72c2\u6b4c\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, a series of parodies of the original ''Ogura'' collection.\n\n==Card game==\nTeika's anthology is the basis for the card game of ''[[karuta]]'', which has been popular since the [[Edo period]].<ref>[[William H. Honan|Honan, William H.]] [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/06/books/why-millions-in-japan-read-all-about-poetry.html?scp=26&sq=Donald+Keene&st=nyt  \"Why Millions in Japan Read All About Poetry,\"] ''New York Times.'' March 6, 2000.</ref>\n\nMany forms of playing games with ''Hyakunin Isshu'' exist in Japan, such as ''[[Uta-garuta]]'', the basis for [[competitive karuta]] (''ky\u014dgi karuta'').\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nisonin]], Kyoto\n* [[Shigureden]], a museum in Kyoto about this subject\n\n==References==\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Thomas Galt. (1982). [https://books.google.com/books?id=4yuXGwAACAAJ&dq=The+Little+Treasury+of+One+Hundred+People,+One+Poem+Each&client=firefox-a  ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each.''] Princeton: [[Princeton University Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-691-06514-4}}\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Yoritsuna Utsunomiya, William Ninnis Porter. (1979) [https://books.google.com/books?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&client=firefox-a  ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu: Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu.''] Tokyo: [[Tuttle Publishing]]. {{ISBN|978-4-8053-0853-0}}\n* Mostow, Joshua S., ed. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Pictures+of+the+Heart:+The+Hyakunin+Isshu+in+Word+and+Image.&client=firefox-a  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image.''] Honolulu: [[University of Hawaii Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-8248-1705-3}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/pictures-of-the-heart-the-hyakunin-isshu-in-word-and-image/oclc/645187818 OCLC 645187818]\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Translation of the Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', Peter McMillan, foreword by Donald Keene. New York: Columbia University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-231-14398-1}} <!-- http://cup.columbia.edu/book/978-0-231-14398-1/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each -->\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'', Peter McMillan. London: Penguin Classics, 2018. {{ISBN|9780141395937}} <!-- https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/269418/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each/ -->\n* ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'', Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, translators. Tokyo: PIE Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-4-89444-757-8}} <!-- http://www.piebooks.com/search/detail.php?ID=1108 -->  This book is also available as an iPad/iPhone application.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Hyakunin Isshu}}\n{{Wikisource|Ogura Hyakunin Isshu|''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''}}\n*[http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/hyakunin/index.html ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu - 100 Poems by 100 Poets''] at [[University of Virginia]] Library Japanese Text Initiative\n* {{librivox book | dtitle=Ogura Hyakunin Isshu | stitle=o | | author=Teika no FUJIWARA}}\n\n{{Japanese poetry}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese literature]]\n[[Category:Japanese poetry anthologies]]\n[[Category:Articles containing Japanese poems]]\n[[Category:Fujiwara no Teika]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n[[Image:Hyakuninisshu 001.jpg|thumb|First poem card of the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', featuring [[Emperor Tenji]]]]\n[[Image:Ogura Shikishi.jpg|thumb|Ogura ''{{wt|ja|\u8272\u7d19|shikishi}}'' by Teika]]\n{{nihongo|'''''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'''''|\u5c0f\u5009\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}} is a classical Japanese anthology of one hundred Japanese [[Waka (poetry)|''waka'']] by one hundred poets. ''Hyakunin isshu'' can be translated to \"one hundred people, one poem [each]\"; it can also refer to the card game of ''[[uta-garuta]]'', which uses a deck composed of cards based on the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''.\n\nIt was compiled by [[Fujiwara no Teika]] while he lived in the [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Ogura district]] of [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]].<ref>Mostow, Joshua. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA25&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image,'' p.25.]</ref>\n\n==Compilation==\nOne of Teika's diaries, the ''Meigetsuki'', says that his son [[Fujiwara no Tameie|Tameie]] asked him to arrange one hundred poems for Tameie's father-in-law, [[Utsunomiya Yoritsuna]], who was furnishing a residence near [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Mount Ogura]];<ref>Ogurayama: Latitude: 34\u00b0 53' 60 N, Longitude: 135\u00b0 46' 60 E; Kyoto Prefecture web site: [http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search  northwest of Arashiyama Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112301/http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search |date=2011-07-22 }}.</ref> hence the full name of ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''. In order to decorate screens of the residence, [[Fujiwara no Teika]] produced the calligraphy poem sheets.<ref>Mostow, [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA94&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  p.94.]</ref>\n\n[[Hishikawa Moronobu]] provided woodblock portraits for each of the poets included in the anthology.<ref name=\"wdl2929\">{{cite web|title=100 Poems by 100 Poets|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/2929/|website=[[World Digital Library]]|date=1680|accessdate=7 June 2013|language=Japanese|author1=Hishikawa, Moronobu\n|author2=Fujiwara, Sadaie}}</ref>\n\nIn his own lifetime, Teika was better known for other work.  For example, in 1200 (''Sh\u014dji 2''), Teika prepared another anthology of one hundred poems for ex-[[Emperor Go-Toba]]. This was called the ''Sh\u014dji Hyakushu''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brower|first=Robert H.|title=Fujiwara Teika's Hundred-Poem Sequence of the Sh\u014dji Era|jstor=2384210|journal=[[Monumenta Nipponica]]|volume=31|issue=3|date=Autumn 1976|pages=223\u2013249|doi=10.2307/2384210}}</ref>\n\n==Poets==\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor Tenji]]|\u5929\u667a\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Empress Jit\u014d]]|\u6301\u7d71\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kakinomoto no Hitomaro]]|\u67ff\u672c\u4eba\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Yamabe no Akahito]]|\u5c71\u90e8\u8d64\u4eba}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sarumaru Day\u016b]]|\u733f\u4e38\u5927\u592b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ch\u016bnagon|Middle Councillor]] [[\u014ctomo no Yakamochi|Yakamochi]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5bb6\u6301}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Abe no Nakamaro]]|\u963f\u500d\u4ef2\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Kisen]]|\u559c\u64b0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ono no Komachi]]|\u5c0f\u91ce\u5c0f\u753a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Semimaru]]|\u8749\u4e38}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Ono no Takamura|Takamura]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7bc1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[High priest|High Priest]] [[Henj\u014d]]|\u50e7\u6b63\u904d\u662d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Y\u014dzei]]|\u967d\u6210\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no T\u014dru|Minister of the Left of Kawara]]|\u6cb3\u539f\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor K\u014dk\u014d]]|\u5149\u5b5d\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Ariwara no Yukihira|Yukihira]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u884c\u5e73}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ariwara no Narihira]] ''[[Ason]]''|\u5728\u539f\u696d\u5e73\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Toshiyuki]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u654f\u884c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Lady Ise|Ise]]|\u4f0a\u52e2}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Prince Motoyoshi]]|\u5143\u826f\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Sosei]]|\u7d20\u6027\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Yasuhide]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u5eb7\u79c0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014ce no Chisato]]|\u5927\u6c5f\u5343\u91cc}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sugawara no Michizane|Kanke]]|\u83c5\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sadakata|Minister of the Right of Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadahira|Teishin-k\u014d]]|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Kanesuke|Kanesuke]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u517c\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Muneyuki]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u5b97\u4e8e\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cshik\u014dchi no Mitsune]]|\u51e1\u6cb3\u5185\u8eac\u6052}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadamine]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u5c91}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sakanoue no Korenori]]|\u5742\u4e0a\u662f\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Harumichi no Tsuraki]]|\u6625\u9053\u5217\u6a39}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tomonori]]|\u7d00\u53cb\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Okikaze]]|\u85e4\u539f\u8208\u98a8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tsurayuki]]|\u7d00\u8cab\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Fukayabu]]|\u6e05\u539f\u6df1\u990a\u7236}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Asayasu]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u671d\u5eb7}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ukon (poet)|Ukon]]|\u53f3\u8fd1}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Minamoto no Hitoshi|Hitoshi]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7b49}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taira no Kanemori]]|\u5e73\u517c\u76db}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadami]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u898b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Motosuke]]|\u6e05\u539f\u5143\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Atsutada|Atsutada]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u6566\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Asatada|Asatada]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u671d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Koretada|Kentoku-k\u014d]]|\u8b19\u5fb3\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sone no Yoshitada]]|\u66fd\u79b0\u597d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Egy\u014d]]|\u6075\u6176\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Shigeyuki]]|\u6e90\u91cd\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cnakatomi no Yoshinobu]] ''Ason''|\u5927\u4e2d\u81e3\u80fd\u5ba3\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Yoshitaka]]|\u85e4\u539f\u7fa9\u5b5d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sanekata]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u5b9f\u65b9\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Michinobu]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u9053\u4fe1\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Michitsuna no Haha|Mother of the Right Captain Michitsuna]]|\u53f3\u5927\u5c06\u9053\u7db1\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Takashina no Takako|Mother of the Honorary Grand Minister]]|\u5100\u540c\u4e09\u53f8\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Dainagon|Upper Coucillor]] [[Fujiwara no Kint\u014d|Kint\u014d]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u516c\u4efb}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Izumi Shikibu]]|\u548c\u6cc9\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Murasaki Shikibu]]|\u7d2b\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Daini no Sanmi]]|\u5927\u5f10\u4e09\u4f4d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Akazome Emon]]|\u8d64\u67d3\u885b\u9580}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Koshikibu no Naishi]]|\u5c0f\u5f0f\u90e8\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ise no Taifu]]|\u4f0a\u52e2\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sei Sh\u014dnagon]]|\u6e05\u5c11\u7d0d\u8a00}}\n# {{nihongo|Chief Magistrate of the Left [[Fujiwara no Michimasa|Michimasa]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9053\u96c5}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Sadayori|Sadayori]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u983c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sagami (poet)|Sagami]]|\u76f8\u6a21}}\n# {{nihongo|Archbishop [[Gy\u014dson]]|\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u884c\u5c0a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Su\u014d no Naishi]]|\u5468\u9632\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[N\u014din]]|\u80fd\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Ry\u014dzen]]|\u826f\u66b9\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Upper Councillor [[Minamoto no Tsunenobu|Tsunenobu]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u7d4c\u4fe1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Y\u016bshi Naishinn\u014d-ke no Kii|Kii of Princess Y\u016bshi's Household]]|\u7950\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b\u5bb6\u7d00\u4f0a}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[\u014ce no Masafusa|Masafusa]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5321\u623f}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Toshiyori]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u4fca\u983c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Mototoshi]]|\u85e4\u539f\u57fa\u4fca}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadamichi|Lay Priest of Hossh\u014d-ji Temple, former ''Kampaku'' and Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u6cd5\u6027\u5bfa\u5165\u9053\u524d\u95a2\u767d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sutoku]]|\u5d07\u5fb3\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Kanemasa]]|\u6e90\u517c\u660c}}\n# {{nihongo|Chief Magistrate of the Left [[Fujiwara no Akisuke|Akisuke]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9855\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taikenmon'in no Horikawa|Horikawa, attendant to Empress Taiken]]|\u5f85\u8ce2\u9580\u9662\u5800\u6cb3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Tokudaiji Sanesada|Later Tokudaiji Minister of the Left]]|\u5f8c\u5fb3\u5927\u5bfa\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[D\u014din]]|\u9053\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Master of the Empress Dowager's Household [[Fujiwara no Shunzei|Shunzei/Toshinari]]|\u7687\u592a\u540e\u5bae\u5927\u592b\u4fca\u6210}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Kiyosuke]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u6e05\u8f14\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Shun'e]]|\u4fca\u6075\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Saigy\u014d]]|\u897f\u884c\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Jakuren]]|\u5bc2\u84ee\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[K\u014dkamonin no Bett\u014d|Attendant to Empress K\u014dka]]|\u7687\u5609\u9580\u9662\u5225\u5f53}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Princess Shikishi]]|\u5f0f\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Inpumon'in no Tay\u016b|Attendant to Empress Inpu]]|\u6bb7\u5bcc\u9580\u9662\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kuj\u014d Yoshitsune|Goky\u014dgoku Regent and Former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5f8c\u4eac\u6975\u6442\u653f\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Nij\u014din no Sanuki|Sanuki, attendant to retired Emperor Nij\u014d]]|\u4e8c\u6761\u9662\u8b83\u5c90}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Sanetomo|Minister of the Right of Kamakura]]|\u938c\u5009\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Asukai no Masatsune|Masatsune]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u96c5\u7d4c}}\n# {{nihongo|Former Archbishop [[Jien]]|\u524d\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u6148\u5186}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Saionji Kintsune|Lay Priest and Former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5165\u9053\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Teika|Teika/Sadaie]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|Junior Second Rank [[Fujiwara no Ietaka|Ietaka]]|\u5f93\u4e8c\u4f4d\u5bb6\u9686}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Go-Toba]]|\u5f8c\u9ce5\u7fbd\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Juntoku]]|\u9806\u5fb3\u9662}}\n\n==Poems==\n[[File:Hyakunin Isshu.JPG|thumb|right|250px|An [[Edo period|Edo-period]] illustrated ''Hyakunin Isshu'' book, with Priest Kisen and Ono no Komachi.]]\n\n===Poem number 2===\nA visually-descriptive poem attributed to [[Empress Jit\u014d]]. Teika chose this poem from the ''[[Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b]]'':\n\n{{waka\n|\u6625\u904e\u304e\u3066\u590f\u6765\u306b\u3051\u3089\u3057{{wt|ja|\u767d\u5999\u306e}}|\u8863\u5e72\u3059\u3066\u3075\u5929\u306e\u9999\u5177\u5c71\n|reading = haru sugite natsu kinikerashi shirotae no<br/>koromo hosu ch\u014d Ama no Kaguyama\n|translation = Spring has passed, and the white robes of summer are being aired on fragrant Mount Kagu\u2014beloved of the gods.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Teika|translator-last1=MacMillan|translator-first1=Peter|date=2018|title=One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse|publisher=Penguin UK|isbn=9780141395944}}</ref>\n|source = ''Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b'' 3:175\n}}\n\nThe original was likely based from a poem of the ''[[Man'y\u014dsh\u016b]]'' (book 1, poem 28) by the same poet.\n\n===Poem number 26===\nA quite different poem is attributed to ''[[Minister of the Left|Sadaijin]]'' [[Fujiwara no Tadahira]] in the context of a very specific incident.  After abdicating, former [[Emperor Uda]] visited Mount Ogura in [[Yamashiro Province]]. He was so greatly impressed by the beauty of autumn colours of the maples that he ordered Fujiwara no Tadahira to encourage Uda's son and heir, [[Emperor Daigo]], to visit the same area.\n\n{{nihongo|Prince Tenshin or Teishin|{{wt|ja|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}|''Teishin-k\u014d''}} was Tadahira's posthumous name, and this is the name used in William Porter's translation of the poem which observes that \"[t]he maples of Mount Ogura / If they could understand / Would keep their brilliant leaves / until [t]he Ruler of this land / Pass with his Royal band.\"  The accompanying 18th century illustration shows a person of consequence riding an ox in a procession with attendants on foot.  The group is passing through an area of maple leaves.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Sadaie|translator-last1=Porter|translator-first1=William N.|date=2007|title=A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the ''Hyakunin Isshu''|edition=illustrated, reprint|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&pg=PA26&dq=hyakunin+ogura#PPA26,M1|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=9784805308530|pages=25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nTeika chose this poem from the ''[[Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b]]'' for the hundred poems collection:\n\n{{waka|\u5c0f\u5009\u5c71\u5cf0\u306e\u3082\u307f\u3062\u8449\u5fc3\u3042\u3089\u3070|\u4eca\u3072\u3068\u305f\u3073\u306e\u884c\u5e78\u307e\u305f\u306a\u3080|reading = Ogura-yama mine no momijiba kokoro araba<br/>ima hitotabi no miyuki matanan<ref>The modern romanization of the last line would be ''miyuki '''matanamu''''' (\u201cawait the emperor's pilgrimage\u201d); by applying the [[historical kana orthography]], ''matanamu'' would be pronounced ''matana'''n'''''.</ref>|translation = Maple leaves on Ogura mountain: if you had a heart, I would have you wait for one more royal visit!<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kamens|first1=Edward|last2=Kamens|first2=Howard I.|date=1997|title=Utamakura, Allusion, and Intertextuality in Traditional Japanese Poetry|edition=illustrated|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300068085|page=102}}</ref>|source = ''Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b'' 17:1128}}\n\n==English translations==\nThe ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'' has been translated into many languages and into English many times, beginning with [[Yone Noguchi]]'s ''Hyaku Nin Isshu in English'' in 1907.<ref>Yone Noguchi, [http://www.h.ehime-u.ac.jp/-marx/YN/articles/hyakunin.htm Hyaku Nin Isshu in English, ''Waseda Bungaku'' (1907)]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOther translations include:\n* William N. Porter, ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan'' (1909)\n* Clay MacCauley, ''Hyakunin-isshu (Single Songs of a Hundred Poets)'' (1917)\n* Tom Galt, ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each'' (1982)\n* Joshua S. Mostow, ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image'' (1996)\n* Peter MacMillan, ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'' (2008; [[Penguin Classics]], revised edition 2018)\n* Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'' (2008)\n\n==Other Hyakunin Isshu anthologies==\nMany other anthologies compiled along the same criteria\u2014one hundred poems by one hundred poets\u2014include the words ''hyakunin isshu'', notably the [[World War II]]-era {{nihongo|''Aikoku Hyakunin Isshu''|\u611b\u56fd\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, or ''One Hundred Patriotic Poems by One Hundred Poets''. Also important is {{nihongo|''Ky\u014dka Hyakunin Isshu''|\u72c2\u6b4c\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, a series of parodies of the original ''Ogura'' collection.\n\n==Card game==\nTeika's anthology is the basis for the card game of ''[[karuta]]'', which has been popular since the [[Edo period]].<ref>[[William H. Honan|Honan, William H.]] [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/06/books/why-millions-in-japan-read-all-about-poetry.html?scp=26&sq=Donald+Keene&st=nyt  \"Why Millions in Japan Read All About Poetry,\"] ''New York Times.'' March 6, 2000.</ref>\n\nMany forms of playing games with ''Hyakunin Isshu'' exist in Japan, such as ''[[Uta-garuta]]'', the basis for [[competitive karuta]] (''ky\u014dgi karuta'').\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nisonin]], Kyoto\n* [[Shigureden]], a museum in Kyoto about this subject\n\n==References==\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Thomas Galt. (1982). [https://books.google.com/books?id=4yuXGwAACAAJ&dq=The+Little+Treasury+of+One+Hundred+People,+One+Poem+Each&client=firefox-a  ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each.''] Princeton: [[Princeton University Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-691-06514-4}}\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Yoritsuna Utsunomiya, William Ninnis Porter. (1979) [https://books.google.com/books?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&client=firefox-a  ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu: Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu.''] Tokyo: [[Tuttle Publishing]]. {{ISBN|978-4-8053-0853-0}}\n* Mostow, Joshua S., ed. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Pictures+of+the+Heart:+The+Hyakunin+Isshu+in+Word+and+Image.&client=firefox-a  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image.''] Honolulu: [[University of Hawaii Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-8248-1705-3}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/pictures-of-the-heart-the-hyakunin-isshu-in-word-and-image/oclc/645187818 OCLC 645187818]\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Translation of the Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', Peter McMillan, foreword by Donald Keene. New York: Columbia University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-231-14398-1}} <!-- http://cup.columbia.edu/book/978-0-231-14398-1/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each -->\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'', Peter McMillan. London: Penguin Classics, 2018. {{ISBN|9780141395937}} <!-- https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/269418/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each/ -->\n* ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'', Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, translators. Tokyo: PIE Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-4-89444-757-8}} <!-- http://www.piebooks.com/search/detail.php?ID=1108 -->  This book is also available as an iPad/iPhone application.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Hyakunin Isshu}}\n{{Wikisource|Ogura Hyakunin Isshu|''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''}}\n*[http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/hyakunin/index.html ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu - 100 Poems by 100 Poets''] at [[University of Virginia]] Library Japanese Text Initiative\n* {{librivox book | dtitle=Ogura Hyakunin Isshu | stitle=o | | author=Teika no FUJIWARA}}\n\n{{Japanese poetry}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese literature]]\n[[Category:Japanese poetry anthologies]]\n[[Category:Articles containing Japanese poems]]\n[[Category:Fujiwara no Teika]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ogura_Hyakunin_Isshu"}
{"title_page": "Brain death", "text_new": "{{for|the EP by Nuclear Assault|Brain Death (EP)}}\n{{Redirect|Brain-dead||Brain Dead (disambiguation){{!}}Brain Dead}}\n\n'''Brain death''' is the complete loss of [[brain activity|brain function]] (including involuntary activity necessary to sustain life).<ref name=\"enc bd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deathreference.com/Bl-Ce/Brain-Death.html |title=Brain death| work=Encyclopedia of Death and Dying| accessdate= 25 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web| url=http://www.uptodate.com/contents/diagnosis-of-brain-death?source=search_result&search=brain+death&selectedTitle=1~37 | title=Diagnosis of brain death| last=Young | first= G Bryan| work=UpToDate|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.4103/0972-5229.53108| pmid = 19881172| title = The diagnosis of brain death| journal = Indian Journal of Critical Care Medicine| volume = 13| issue = 1| pages = 7\u201311| year = 2009| last1 = Goila | first1 = A. | last2 = Pawar | first2 = M. | pmc = 2772257}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.4081/ni.2010.e2| pmid = 21577338| pmc = 3093212| title = Diagnosis of brain death| journal = Neurology International| volume = 2| issue = 1| pages = 2| year = 2010| last1 = Machado | first1 = C. }}</ref> It differs from [[persistent vegetative state]], in which the person is alive and some autonomic functions remain.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Medical Aspects of the Persistent Vegetative State|first=The Multi-Society Task Force on|last=PVS|date=26 May 1994|publisher=|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=330|issue=21|pages=1499\u20131508|doi=10.1056/nejm199405263302107|pmid = 7818633}}</ref> It is also distinct from an ordinary [[coma]], whether induced medically or caused by injury and/or illness, even if it is very deep, as long as some brain and bodily activity and function remain; and it is also not the same as the condition known as [[locked-in syndrome]]. A [[differential diagnosis]] can medically distinguish these differing conditions.\n\nBrain death is used as an indicator of [[legal death]] in many jurisdictions, but it is [[Medical definition of death|defined]] inconsistently and often confused by the public.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://journal.chestnet.org/action/captchaChallenge?redirectUri=%2Farticle%2FS0012-3692%2818%2930150-8%2Ffulltext|title=CHEST|last=Jones|first=A|journal=Chest|volume=154|issue=2|pages=286\u2013292|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2018.01.021|pmid=29382473|access-date=2018-12-27|year=2018}}</ref> Various parts of the brain may keep functioning when others do not anymore, and the term \"brain death\" has been used to refer to various combinations. For example, although one major medical dictionary<ref name=\"Dorlands\">{{Citation |author=Elsevier |authorlink=Elsevier |title=Dorland's Illustrated Medical Dictionary |publisher=Elsevier |url=http://dorlands.com/ |postscript=.}}</ref> considers \"brain death\" to be synonymous with \"cerebral death\" (death of the [[cerebrum]]), the US National Library of Medicine [[Medical Subject Headings]] (MeSH) system defines brain death as including the [[brainstem]]. The distinctions are medically significant because, for example, in someone with a dead [[cerebrum]] but a living [[brainstem]], spontaneous breathing may continue unaided, whereas in whole-brain death (which includes [[brainstem death]]), only [[life support]] equipment would maintain [[ventilation (physiology)|ventilation]]. Patients classified as brain-dead can have their organs surgically removed for [[organ donation]].\n\n==Legal history==\n\nTraditionally, both the legal and medical communities determined [[death]] through the permanent end of certain [[Human body|bodily]] functions in [[clinical death]], especially [[Respiration (physiology)|respiration]] and [[Cardiac cycle|heartbeat]].  With the increasing ability of the medical community to resuscitate people with no respiration, heartbeat, or other external signs of life, the need for another definition of death occurred, raising questions of [[legal death]]. This gained greater urgency with the widespread use of [[life support]] equipment, as well as rising capabilities and demand for [[organ transplantation]].\n\nSince the 1960s, laws on determining death have, therefore, been implemented in all countries with active organ transplantation programs. The first European country to adopt brain death as a legal definition (or indicator) of death was [[Finland]] in 1971. In the [[United States]], [[Kansas]] had enacted a similar law earlier.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | author=(Randell T. | title=Medical and legal considerations of brain death | journal=Acta Anaesthesiologica Scandinavica | volume=48 | issue=2 | year=2004 | pages=139\u2013144 | pmid=14995934 | doi=10.1111/j.0001-5172.2004.00304.x}}</ref>\n\nAn ''[[ad hoc]]'' committee at [[Harvard Medical School]] published a pivotal 1968 report to define irreversible [[coma]].<ref>{{cite journal | year = 1968 | title = A definition of irreversible coma: report of the Ad Hoc Committee of the Harvard Medical School to Examine the Definition of Brain Death | url = | journal = JAMA | volume = 205 | issue = 6| pages = 337\u201340 | doi=10.1001/jama.1968.03140320031009| pmid = 5694976 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rAz4nl35KkIC&pg=PA59|title=Life-sustaining technologies and the elderly.|publisher=DIANE Publishing|via=Google Books|isbn=9781428922815|year=1987}}</ref> The Harvard criteria gradually gained consensus toward what is now known as brain death. In the wake of the 1976 [[Karen Ann Quinlan case]], state legislatures in the United States moved to accept brain death as an acceptable indication of death. In 1981 a Presidential commission issued a landmark report \u2013 ''Defining Death: Medical, Legal, and Ethical Issues in the Determination of Death'' <ref>{{cite document|title=Defining death: a report on the medical, legal and ethical issues in the determination of death|hdl=1805/707|date=July 1981}}</ref> \u2013 that rejected the \"higher brain\" approach to death in favor of a \"whole brain\" definition. This report was the basis for the [[Uniform Determination of Death Act]], which has been enacted in 39 states of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legislative Fact Sheet \u2013 Determination of Death Act|url=http://uniformlaws.org/LegislativeFactSheet.aspx?title=Determination%20of%20Death%20Act|publisher=Uniform Law Commission|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> The Uniform Determination of Death Act in the United States attempts to standardize criteria. Today, both the legal and medical communities in the US use \"brain death\" as a legal definition of death, allowing a person to be declared [[legal death|legally dead]] even if life support equipment keeps the body's metabolic processes working.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pntb.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Uniform-Determination-of-Death-1980_5c.pdf | title=Uniform Determination of Death Act | publisher=National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws| accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK, the Royal College of Physicians reported in 1995, abandoning the 1979 claim that the tests published in 1976 sufficed for the diagnosis of brain death and suggesting a new definition of death based on the irreversible loss of brain stem function alone.<ref>Criteria for the diagnosis of brain stem death. J Roy Coll Physns of London 1995;29:381-2</ref> This new definition, the irreversible loss of the capacity for consciousness and for spontaneous breathing, and the essentially unchanged 1976 tests held to establish that state, have been adopted as a basis of death certification for organ transplant purposes in subsequent Codes of Practice.<ref>A Code of Practice for the Diagnosis and Confirmation of Death. Academy of Medical Royal Colleges. 70 Wimpole Street, London, 2008</ref><ref>American Academy of Neurology. (2000, January 13).Spontaneous Movements Often Occur After Brain Death.Science Daily.</ref> The Australia and New Zealand Intensive Care Society (ANZICS) states that the \"determination of brain death requires that there is unresponsive coma, the absence of brain-stem reflexes and the absence of respiratory centre function, in the clinical setting in which these findings are irreversible. In particular, there must be definite clinical or neuro-imaging evidence of acute brain pathology (e.g. traumatic brain injury, intracranial haemorrhage, hypoxic encephalopathy) consistent with the irreversible loss of neurological function.\"<ref>http://www.anzics.com.au/Downloads/ANZICS%20Statement%20on%20%20Death%20and%20Organ%20Donation%20Edition%203.2.pdf</ref>\n\n==Medical criteria==\nNatural movements also known as the [[Lazarus sign]] or Lazarus reflex can occur on a brain-dead person whose organs have been kept functioning by life support. The living cells that can cause these movements are not living cells from the brain or brain stem; these cells come from the spinal cord. Sometimes these body movements can cause false hope for family members.\n\nA brain-dead individual has no clinical evidence of brain function upon [[physical examination]]. This includes no response to [[pain]] and no [[cranial nerve]] [[reflex]]es. Reflexes include [[Pupil constriction|pupillary response]] (fixed pupils), [[oculocephalic reflex]], [[corneal reflex]], no response to the [[caloric reflex test]], and no spontaneous [[Respiratory system|respiration]]s.\n\nBrain death can sometimes be difficult to differentiate from other medical states such as [[barbiturate overdose]], [[alcohol intoxication]], [[sedative]] overdose, [[hypothermia]], [[hypoglycemia]], [[coma]], and chronic [[vegetative states]]. Some comatose patients can recover to pre-coma or near pre-coma level of functioning, and some patients with severe irreversible neurological dysfunction will nonetheless retain some lower brain functions, such as spontaneous respiration, despite the losses of both cortex and brain stem functionality. Such is the case with [[anencephaly]].\n\nBrain electrical activity can stop completely, or drop to such a low level as to be undetectable with most equipment. An [[electroencephalogram|EEG]] will therefore be flat, though this is sometimes also observed during deep [[anesthesia]] or [[cardiac arrest]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Karasawa | first1 = H | display-authors = etal   | date = Jan 2001 | title = Intracranial electroencephalographic changes in deep anesthesia | url = | journal = Clin Neurophysiol | volume = 112 | issue = 1| pages = 25\u201330 | pmid = 11137657 | doi=10.1016/s1388-2457(00)00510-1}}</ref> Although in the United States a flat EEG test is not required to certify death, it is considered to have confirmatory value. In the UK it is not considered to be of value because any continuing activity it might reveal in parts of the brain above the brain stem is held to be irrelevant to the diagnosis of death on the Code of Practice criteria.<ref>A Code of Practice for the Diagnosis of Death. Academy of Medical Royal Colleges, 70 Wimpole Street, London, 2008</ref>\n\nThe diagnosis of brain death is often required to be highly rigorous, in order to be certain that the condition is irreversible. Legal criteria vary, but in general require neurological examinations by two independent physicians. The exams must show complete and irreversible absence of brain function (brain stem function in UK),<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/92/5/760.full |title=Difficulty in brainstem death testing in the presence of high spinal cord injury |first=C. E. |last=Waters |first2=G. |last2=French |first3=M. |last3=Burt |journal=British Journal of Anaesthesia |volume=92 |issue=5 |pages=760\u20134 |doi=10.1093/bja/aeh117|pmid=15113764 |year=2004 }}</ref> and may include two isoelectric (flat-line) EEGs 24&nbsp;hours apart (less in other countries where it is accepted that if the cause of the dysfunction is a clear physical trauma there is no need to wait that long to establish irreversibility). The patient should have a normal temperature and be free of drugs that can suppress brain activity if the diagnosis is to be made on EEG criteria.\n\n[[File:Radionuclide Cerebral Blood Flow Scan.png|thumb|Radionuclide scan: No intracranial blood flow. The [[Hot nose sign|\"hot-nose\" sign]] is shown.]]\nAlso, a [[radionuclide]] cerebral blood flow scan that shows complete absence of intracranial blood flow must be considered with other exams \u2013 temporary swelling of the brain, particularly within the first 72 hours, can lead to a false positive test on a patient that may recover with more time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theness.com/neurologicablog/index.php/brain-dead/|title=Brain Dead - NeuroLogica Blog|website=theness.com|date=2008-04-08}}</ref>\n\n[[CT angiography]] is neither required nor sufficient test to make the diagnosis.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=T|last2=Dineen|first2=RA|last3=Gardiner|first3=DC|last4=Buss|first4=CH|last5=Howatson|first5=A|last6=Pace|first6=NL|title=Computed tomography (CT) angiography for confirmation of the clinical diagnosis of brain death.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=Mar 31, 2014|volume=3|issue=3|pages=CD009694|pmid=24683063|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD009694.pub2|pmc=6517290}}</ref>\n\nConfirmatory testing is only needed under the age of 1.<ref name=\":0\" /> For children and adults, testing is optional.  Other situations possibly requiring confirmatory testing include severe facial trauma where determination of brainstem reflexes will be difficult, pre-existing pupillary abnormalities, and patients with severe sleep apnea and/or pulmonary disease.<ref name=\":0\" /> Confirmatory tests include: cerebral angiography, electroencephalography, transcranial Doppler ultrasonography, and cerebral scintigraphy (technetium Tc 99m exametazime).  Cerebral angiography is considered the most sensitive confirmatory test in the determination of brain death.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Organ donation==\n{{Main|Organ donation}}\nWhile the diagnosis of brain death has become accepted as a basis for the certification of death for legal purposes, it is a very different state from biological death - the state universally recognized and understood as death.<ref>Truog RD, Miller FG. The meaning of brain death. JAMA Internal Medicine 2014, Publ online June 9, 2014 : http://archinte.jamanetwork.com</ref> The continuing function of vital organs in the bodies of those diagnosed brain dead, if mechanical ventilation and other life-support measures are continued, provides optimal opportunities for their transplantation.\n\nWhen mechanical ventilation is used to support the body of a brain dead organ donor pending a transplant into an organ recipient, the donor's date of death is listed as the date that brain death was diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding Brain Death|url=http://www.donorrecovery.org/learn/understanding-brain-death/|quote=What is the legal time of death for a brain dead patient?  The legal time of death is the date and time that doctors determine that all brain activity has ceased. This is the time that is noted on the patient\u2019s death certificate.}}</ref>\n\nIn some countries (for instance, [[Spain]],<ref>[http://www.ont.es/informacion/P\u00e1ginas/Donaci%C3%B3n.aspx Organizaci\u00f3n Nacional de Transplantes \u2013 Consentimiento familiar y donaci\u00f3n]</ref> [[Finland]], [[Wales]], [[Portugal]], and [[France]]), everyone is automatically an organ donor after diagnosis of death on legally accepted criteria, although some jurisdictions (such as [[Singapore]], [[Spain]], [[Wales]], [[France]], [[Czech Republic]], [[Poland]] and [[Portugal]]) allow opting out of the system. Elsewhere, consent from family members or next-of-kin may be required for organ donation. In [[New Zealand]], [[Australia]], the [[United Kingdom]] (excluding [[Wales]]) and most states in the [[United States]], drivers are asked upon application if they wish to be registered as an organ donor.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Donate Life America Donor Designation State Report Card 2013|url=http://donatelife.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/DLA_ReportCardFinal_2013.pdf|pages=6 & 7|quote=2012 State Comparisons|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322222952/http://donatelife.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/DLA_ReportCardFinal_2013.pdf|archivedate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, if the patient is at or near death, the hospital must notify a transplant organization of the person's details and maintain the patient while the patient is being evaluated for suitability as a donor.<ref>{{cite web|title=State and Federal Law on Organ Procurement|url=http://www.wsha.org/EOL-OrganProcurement.cfm|quote=Unless the individual expressed contrary intent, a hospital must take measures to ensure the medical suitability of an individual at or near death while a procurement organization examines the patient for suitability as a donor.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306072928/http://www.wsha.org/EOL-OrganProcurement.cfm|archivedate=2014-03-06}}</ref> The patient is kept on ventilator support until the organs have been surgically removed. If the patient has indicated in an [[advance health care directive]] that they do not wish to receive [[mechanical ventilation]] or has specified a [[do not resuscitate]] order and the patient has also indicated that they wish to donate their organs, some vital organs such as the heart and lungs may not be able to be recovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions About Donation|url=http://health.mo.gov/living/organdonor/faq.php|quote=DNR will be honored. You can still be a tissue donor.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Medicine}}\n{{col div|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Brainstem death]]\n* [[Clinical death]]\n* [[Death]]\n* [[Persistent vegetative state]]\n* [[Information-theoretic death]]\n* [[Consciousness after death]]\n* [[Klaus Sch\u00e4fer (catholic theologian)|Klaus Sch\u00e4fer]], [https://epub.uni-regensburg.de/36456/1/verstehen.pdf Understand brain death PDF in German]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 1572\n| ICD10           = \n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|348.82}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = D001926\n| ICD10CM         = {{ICD10CM|G93.82}}\n}}\n{{disorders of consciousness}}\n{{Death}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brain Death}}\n[[Category:Medical aspects of death]]\n[[Category:Anatomical pathology]]\n[[Category:Brain]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the EP by Nuclear Assault|Brain Death (EP)}}\n{{Redirect|Brain-dead||Brain Dead (disambiguation){{!}}Brain Dead}}\n\n'''Brain death''' is the complete loss of [[brain activity|brain function]] (including involuntary activity necessary to sustain life).<ref name=\"enc bd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deathreference.com/Bl-Ce/Brain-Death.html |title=Brain death| work=Encyclopedia of Death and Dying| accessdate= 25 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web| url=http://www.uptodate.com/contents/diagnosis-of-brain-death?source=search_result&search=brain+death&selectedTitle=1~37 | title=Diagnosis of brain death| last=Young | first= G Bryan| work=UpToDate|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.4103/0972-5229.53108| pmid = 19881172| title = The diagnosis of brain death| journal = Indian Journal of Critical Care Medicine| volume = 13| issue = 1| pages = 7\u201311| year = 2009| last1 = Goila | first1 = A. | last2 = Pawar | first2 = M. | pmc = 2772257}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.4081/ni.2010.e2| pmid = 21577338| pmc = 3093212| title = Diagnosis of brain death| journal = Neurology International| volume = 2| issue = 1| pages = 2| year = 2010| last1 = Machado | first1 = C. }}</ref> It differs from [[persistent vegetative state]], in which the person is alive and some autonomic functions remain.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Medical Aspects of the Persistent Vegetative State|first=The Multi-Society Task Force on|last=PVS|date=26 May 1994|publisher=|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=330|issue=21|pages=1499\u20131508|doi=10.1056/nejm199405263302107|pmid = 7818633}}</ref> It is also distinct from an ordinary [[coma]], whether induced medically or caused by injury and/or illness, even if it is very deep, as long as some brain and bodily activity and function remain; and it is also not the same as the condition known as [[locked-in syndrome]]. A [[differential diagnosis]] can medically distinguish these differing conditions.\n\nBrain death is used as an indicator of [[legal death]] in many jurisdictions, but it is [[Medical definition of death|defined]] inconsistently and often confused by the public.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://journal.chestnet.org/action/captchaChallenge?redirectUri=%2Farticle%2FS0012-3692%2818%2930150-8%2Ffulltext|title=CHEST|last=Jones|first=A|journal=Chest|volume=154|issue=2|pages=286\u2013292|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2018.01.021|pmid=29382473|access-date=2018-12-27|year=2018}}</ref> Various parts of the brain may keep functioning when others do not anymore, and the term \"brain death\" has been used to refer to various combinations. For example, although one major medical dictionary<ref name=\"Dorlands\">{{Citation |author=Elsevier |authorlink=Elsevier |title=Dorland's Illustrated Medical Dictionary |publisher=Elsevier |url=http://dorlands.com/ |postscript=.}}</ref> considers \"brain death\" to be synonymous with \"cerebral death\" (death of the [[cerebrum]]), the US National Library of Medicine [[Medical Subject Headings]] (MeSH) system defines brain death as including the [[brainstem]]. The distinctions are medically significant because, for example, in someone with a dead [[cerebrum]] but a living [[brainstem]], spontaneous breathing may continue unaided, whereas in whole-brain death (which includes [[brainstem death]]), only [[life support]] equipment would maintain [[ventilation (physiology)|ventilation]]. Patients classified as brain-dead can have their organs surgically removed for [[organ donation]].\n\n==Legal history==\n\nTraditionally, both the legal and medical communities determined [[death]] through the permanent end of certain [[Human body|bodily]] functions in [[clinical death]], especially [[Respiration (physiology)|respiration]] and [[Cardiac cycle|heartbeat]].  With the increasing ability of the medical community to resuscitate people with no respiration, heartbeat, or other external signs of life, the need for another definition of death occurred, raising questions of [[legal death]]. This gained greater urgency with the widespread use of [[life support]] equipment, as well as rising capabilities and demand for [[organ transplantation]].\n\nSince the 1960s, laws on determining death have, therefore, been implemented in all countries with active organ transplantation programs. The first European country to adopt brain death as a legal definition (or indicator) of death was [[Finland]] in 1971. In the [[United States]], [[Kansas]] had enacted a similar law earlier.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | author=(Randell T. | title=Medical and legal considerations of brain death | journal=Acta Anaesthesiologica Scandinavica | volume=48 | issue=2 | year=2004 | pages=139\u2013144 | pmid=14995934 | doi=10.1111/j.0001-5172.2004.00304.x}}</ref>\n\nAn ''[[ad hoc]]'' committee at [[Harvard Medical School]] published a pivotal 1968 report to define irreversible [[coma]].<ref>{{cite journal | year = 1968 | title = A definition of irreversible coma: report of the Ad Hoc Committee of the Harvard Medical School to Examine the Definition of Brain Death | url = | journal = JAMA | volume = 205 | issue = 6| pages = 337\u201340 | doi=10.1001/jama.1968.03140320031009| pmid = 5694976 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rAz4nl35KkIC&pg=PA59|title=Life-sustaining technologies and the elderly.|publisher=DIANE Publishing|via=Google Books|isbn=9781428922815|year=1987}}</ref> The Harvard criteria gradually gained consensus toward what is now known as brain death. In the wake of the 1976 [[Karen Ann Quinlan case]], state legislatures in the United States moved to accept brain death as an acceptable indication of death. In 1981 a Presidential commission issued a landmark report \u2013 ''Defining Death: Medical, Legal, and Ethical Issues in the Determination of Death'' <ref>{{cite document|title=Defining death: a report on the medical, legal and ethical issues in the determination of death|hdl=1805/707|date=July 1981}}</ref> \u2013 that rejected the \"higher brain\" approach to death in favor of a \"whole brain\" definition. This report was the basis for the [[Uniform Determination of Death Act]], which has been enacted in 39 states of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legislative Fact Sheet \u2013 Determination of Death Act|url=http://uniformlaws.org/LegislativeFactSheet.aspx?title=Determination%20of%20Death%20Act|publisher=Uniform Law Commission|accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> The Uniform Determination of Death Act in the United States attempts to standardize criteria. Today, both the legal and medical communities in the US use \"brain death\" as a legal definition of death, allowing a person to be declared [[legal death|legally dead]] even if life support equipment keeps the body's metabolic processes working.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pntb.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Uniform-Determination-of-Death-1980_5c.pdf | title=Uniform Determination of Death Act | publisher=National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws| accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK, the Royal College of Physicians reported in 1995, abandoning the 1979 claim that the tests published in 1976 sufficed for the diagnosis of brain death and suggesting a new definition of death based on the irreversible loss of brain stem function alone.<ref>Criteria for the diagnosis of brain stem death. J Roy Coll Physns of London 1995;29:381-2</ref> This new definition, the irreversible loss of the capacity for consciousness and for spontaneous breathing, and the essentially unchanged 1976 tests held to establish that state, have been adopted as a basis of death certification for organ transplant purposes in subsequent Codes of Practice.<ref>A Code of Practice for the Diagnosis and Confirmation of Death. Academy of Medical Royal Colleges. 70 Wimpole Street, London, 2008</ref><ref>American Academy of Neurology. (2000, January 13).Spontaneous Movements Often Occur After Brain Death.Science Daily.</ref> The Australia and New Zealand Intensive Care Society (ANZICS) states that the \"determination of brain death requires that there is unresponsive coma, the absence of brain-stem reflexes and the absence of respiratory centre function, in the clinical setting in which these findings are irreversible. In particular, there must be definite clinical or neuro-imaging evidence of acute brain pathology (e.g. traumatic brain injury, intracranial haemorrhage, hypoxic encephalopathy) consistent with the irreversible loss of neurological function.\"<ref>http://www.anzics.com.au/Downloads/ANZICS%20Statement%20on%20%20Death%20and%20Organ%20Donation%20Edition%203.2.pdf</ref>\n\n==Medical criteria==\nNatural movements also known as the [[Lazarus sign]] or Lazarus reflex can occur on a brain-dead person whose organs have been kept functioning by life support. The living cells that can cause these movements are not living cells from the brain or brain stem; these cells come from the spinal cord. Sometimes these body movements can cause false hope for family members.\n\nA brain-dead individual has no clinical evidence of brain function upon [[physical examination]]. This includes no response to [[pain]] and no [[cranial nerve]] [[reflex]]es. Reflexes include [[Pupil constriction|pupillary response]] (fixed pupils), [[oculocephalic reflex]], [[corneal reflex]], no response to the [[caloric reflex test]], and no spontaneous [[Respiratory system|respiration]]s.\n\nBrain death can sometimes be difficult to differentiate from other medical states such as [[barbiturate overdose]], [[alcohol intoxication]], [[sedative]] overdose, [[hypothermia]], [[hypoglycemia]], [[coma]], and chronic [[vegetative states]]. Some comatose patients can recover to pre-coma or near pre-coma level of functioning, and some patients with severe irreversible neurological dysfunction will nonetheless retain some lower brain functions, such as spontaneous respiration, despite the losses of both cortex and brain stem functionality. Such is the case with [[anencephaly]].\n\nBrain electrical activity can stop completely, or drop to such a low level as to be undetectable with most equipment. An [[electroencephalogram|EEG]] will therefore be flat, though this is sometimes also observed during deep [[anesthesia]] or [[cardiac arrest]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Karasawa | first1 = H | display-authors = etal   | date = Jan 2001 | title = Intracranial electroencephalographic changes in deep anesthesia | url = | journal = Clin Neurophysiol | volume = 112 | issue = 1| pages = 25\u201330 | pmid = 11137657 | doi=10.1016/s1388-2457(00)00510-1}}</ref> Although in the United States a flat EEG test is not required to certify death, it is considered to have confirmatory value. In the UK it is not considered to be of value because any continuing activity it might reveal in parts of the brain above the brain stem is held to be irrelevant to the diagnosis of death on the Code of Practice criteria.<ref>A Code of Practice for the Diagnosis of Death. Academy of Medical Royal Colleges, 70 Wimpole Street, London, 2008</ref>\n\nThe diagnosis of brain death is often required to be highly rigorous, in order to be certain that the condition is irreversible. Legal criteria vary, but in general require neurological examinations by two independent physicians. The exams must show complete and irreversible absence of brain function (brain stem function in UK),<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/92/5/760.full |title=Difficulty in brainstem death testing in the presence of high spinal cord injury |first=C. E. |last=Waters |first2=G. |last2=French |first3=M. |last3=Burt |journal=British Journal of Anaesthesia |volume=92 |issue=5 |pages=760\u20134 |doi=10.1093/bja/aeh117|pmid=15113764 |year=2004 }}</ref> and may include two isoelectric (flat-line) EEGs 24&nbsp;hours apart (less in other countries where it is accepted that if the cause of the dysfunction is a clear physical trauma there is no need to wait that long to establish irreversibility). The patient should have a normal temperature and be free of drugs that can suppress brain activity if the diagnosis is to be made on EEG criteria.\n\n[[File:Radionuclide Cerebral Blood Flow Scan.png|thumb|Radionuclide scan: No intracranial blood flow. The [[Hot nose sign|\"hot-nose\" sign]] is shown.]]\nAlso, a [[radionuclide]] cerebral blood flow scan that shows complete absence of intracranial blood flow must be considered with other exams \u2013 temporary swelling of the brain, particularly within the first 72 hours, can lead to a false positive test on a patient that may recover with more time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theness.com/neurologicablog/index.php/brain-dead/|title=Brain Dead - NeuroLogica Blog|website=theness.com|date=2008-04-08}}</ref>\n\n[[CT angiography]] is neither required nor sufficient test to make the diagnosis.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=T|last2=Dineen|first2=RA|last3=Gardiner|first3=DC|last4=Buss|first4=CH|last5=Howatson|first5=A|last6=Pace|first6=NL|title=Computed tomography (CT) angiography for confirmation of the clinical diagnosis of brain death.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=Mar 31, 2014|volume=3|issue=3|pages=CD009694|pmid=24683063|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD009694.pub2|pmc=6517290}}</ref>\n\nConfirmatory testing is only needed under the age of 1.<ref name=\":0\" /> For children and adults, testing is optional.  Other situations possibly requiring confirmatory testing include severe facial trauma where determination of brainstem reflexes will be difficult, pre-existing pupillary abnormalities, and patients with severe sleep apnea and/or pulmonary disease.<ref name=\":0\" /> Confirmatory tests include: cerebral angiography, electroencephalography, transcranial Doppler ultrasonography, and cerebral scintigraphy (technetium Tc 99m exametazime).  Cerebral angiography is considered the most sensitive confirmatory test in the determination of brain death.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Organ donation==\n{{Main|Organ donation}}\nWhile the diagnosis of brain death has become accepted as a basis for the certification of death for legal purposes, it is a very different state from biological death - the state universally recognized and understood as death.<ref>Truog RD, Miller FG. The meaning of brain death. JAMA Internal Medicine 2014, Publ online June 9, 2014 : http://archinte.jamanetwork.com</ref> The continuing function of vital organs in the bodies of those diagnosed brain dead, if mechanical ventilation and other life-support measures are continued, provides optimal opportunities for their transplantation.\n\nWhen mechanical ventilation is used to support the body of a brain dead organ donor pending a transplant into an organ recipient, the donor's date of death is listed as the date that brain death was diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding Brain Death|url=http://www.donorrecovery.org/learn/understanding-brain-death/|quote=What is the legal time of death for a brain dead patient?  The legal time of death is the date and time that doctors determine that all brain activity has ceased. This is the time that is noted on the patient\u2019s death certificate.}}</ref>\n\nIn some countries (for instance, [[Spain]],<ref>[http://www.ont.es/informacion/P\u00e1ginas/Donaci%C3%B3n.aspx Organizaci\u00f3n Nacional de Transplantes \u2013 Consentimiento familiar y donaci\u00f3n]</ref> [[Finland]], [[Wales]], [[Portugal]], and [[France]]), everyone is automatically an organ donor after diagnosis of death on legally accepted criteria, although some jurisdictions (such as [[Singapore]], [[Spain]], [[Wales]], [[France]], [[Czech Republic]], [[Poland]] and [[Portugal]]) allow opting out of the system. Elsewhere, consent from family members or next-of-kin may be required for organ donation. In [[New Zealand]], [[Australia]], the [[United Kingdom]] (excluding [[Wales]]) and most states in the [[United States]], drivers are asked upon application if they wish to be registered as an organ donor.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Donate Life America Donor Designation State Report Card 2013|url=http://donatelife.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/DLA_ReportCardFinal_2013.pdf|pages=6 & 7|quote=2012 State Comparisons|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322222952/http://donatelife.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/DLA_ReportCardFinal_2013.pdf|archivedate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, if the patient is at or near death, the hospital must notify a transplant organization of the person's details and maintain the patient while the patient is being evaluated for suitability as a donor.<ref>{{cite web|title=State and Federal Law on Organ Procurement|url=http://www.wsha.org/EOL-OrganProcurement.cfm|quote=Unless the individual expressed contrary intent, a hospital must take measures to ensure the medical suitability of an individual at or near death while a procurement organization examines the patient for suitability as a donor.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306072928/http://www.wsha.org/EOL-OrganProcurement.cfm|archivedate=2014-03-06}}</ref> The patient is kept on ventilator support until the organs have been surgically removed. If the patient has indicated in an [[advance health care directive]] that they do not wish to receive [[mechanical ventilation]] or has specified a [[do not resuscitate]] order and the patient has also indicated that they wish to donate their organs, some vital organs such as the heart and lungs may not be able to be recovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions About Donation|url=http://health.mo.gov/living/organdonor/faq.php|quote=DNR will be honored. You can still be a tissue donor.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Medicine}}\n{{col div|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Brainstem death]]\n* [[Clinical death]]\n* [[Death]]\n* [[Persistent vegetative state]]\n* [[Information-theoretic death]]\n* [[Consciousness after death]]\n* [[Klaus Sch\u00e4fer (catholic theologian)|Klaus Sch\u00e4fer]], [https://epub.uni-regensburg.de/36456/1/verstehen.pdf Understand brain death PDF in German]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB     = 1572 \n|  ICD10          = \n|  ICD9           = {{ICD9|348.82}} \n|  ICDO           = \n|  OMIM           = \n|  MedlinePlus    = \n|  eMedicineSubj  = \n|  eMedicineTopic = \n|  MeshID         = D001926\n}}\n{{disorders of consciousness}}\n{{Death}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brain Death}}\n[[Category:Medical aspects of death]]\n[[Category:Anatomical pathology]]\n[[Category:Brain]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_death"}
